comment_data.body: For these two I think we can use the pre-defined `HlGroupID` union, ( and e.g. replacing `object_to_hl_id(dict->global_link, "link", err)` with just `dict->global_link` at the usage site)
That is being handled. String hl name is converted to int by `api_keydict_to_dict` and friends (otherwise the `HLGroupID` type would have served no purpose)

non-blocking, just for your consideration:
```suggestion
  LuaFun((Integer start_a, Integer count_a, Integer start_b, Integer count_b),
```

I chose `LuaRefOf` to be consistent with `DictOf` and `ArrayOf`. To me it would make more sense to rename `LuaRef` to `LuaFun` and `LuaRefOf` to `LuaFunOf`. The only difference with the `Of` variant is extra metadata.

Or does `LuaRef` mean something more general?

> To me it would make more sense to rename `LuaRef` to `LuaFun` and `LuaRefOf` to `LuaFunOf`

That also SGTM.

> Or does `LuaRef` mean something more general?

I think it's a carry-over from Vimscript/typval where function references were called "FuncRefs". Let's be sure @bfredl has no objection though.
Ok. Let's defer this for later then as renaming LuaRef probably deserves its own PR.
`LuaRef` can be any lua value. We use it for tables in some places. It is fine to have specialized typedefs on top of course.
